41 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 10.7. (a) A dental hygienist or dental assistant (as
42 defined in IC 25-14-1-1.5(4)) may administer nitrous oxide under the
HB 1254—LS 6889/DI 148

3
1 direct supervision of a licensed dentist if the dental hygienist or dental
2 assistant has:
3 (1) either:
4 (A) been employed in a dental practice for at least one (1)
5 year; or
6 (B) has graduated from a program:
7 (i) accredited by the Commission on Dental Accreditation of
8 the American Dental Association; or
9 (ii) approved by the board;
10 (2) satisfactorily completed a three (3) hour didactic nitrous oxide
11 administration course that:
12 (A) containing contains curriculum on pharmacology,
13 biochemistry, anatomy of nitrous oxide administration,
14 emergency procedures, and the mechanics of operating a
15 nitrous unit; and
16 (B) is accredited by the Commission on Dental Accreditation
17 of the American Dental Association or approved by the
18 board; and
19 (3) demonstrated clinical competency on at least five (5) patients
20 under the direct supervision of a licensed Indiana dentist whose
21 license is in good standing.
22 (b) The licensed Indiana dentist supervising the clinical competency
23 under subsection (a)(3) shall provide to the dental hygienist or dental
24 assistant a signed affidavit certifying the competency.
25 (c) Upon receipt of the affidavit provided to a dental hygienist or
26 dental assistant under subsection (b), the provider of an educational
27 program or curriculum described in subsection (a)(2) shall issue a
28 certificate of completion to the dental hygienist or dental assistant. The
29 certificate of completion must be publicly displayed in the dental office
30 of the dental hygienist or dental assistant.
31 (d) Before permitting a dental hygienist or dental assistant to
32 administer nitrous oxide, the supervising dentist shall:
33 (1) verify that the dental hygienist or dental assistant has
34 completed the requirements of subsection (a);
35 (2) determine the maximum percent-dosage of nitrous oxide to be
36 administered to the patient; and
37 (3) ensure that any administration or monitoring of nitrous oxide
38 by dental hygienists or dental assistants is done in accordance
39 with relevant guidelines and standards developed by the
40 American Dental Association or the American Academy of
41 Pediatric Dentistry.
